<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
     SECTION 2: WHY THIS AREA
════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section style="background:var(--color-base, #f2efe9); padding:80px 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:800px; margin:0 auto;">
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.15em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c4912a; margin-bottom:1rem;">Local Expertise</p>
    <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:clamp(1.8rem, 3.5vw, 2.8rem); font-weight:300; line-height:1.2; color:#1c1917; margin-bottom:1.75rem;">Affordability, community and consistent rental demand in the western corridor.</h2>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Inala is one of Brisbane's most genuinely multicultural suburbs, sitting around 15 kilometres west of the CBD and surrounded by Darra, Richlands, Forest Lake and Durack. It has built a reputation as one of the most affordable entry points in the western corridor, attracting a broad mix of first home buyers, investors and established multicultural families who value the suburb's diversity and community depth. The housing stock is largely post-war brick, with many homes on generous blocks that still present value-add opportunity for buyers prepared to renovate or extend. That combination of affordability and latent upside has kept both owner-occupier and investor interest consistently present in the market.
    </p>
