    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Transport access is a key part of what makes Inala work for tenants and buyers who rely on public infrastructure. Translink bus routes through the suburb connect to Darra Station on the Ipswich rail line, and from there it is a direct run into the CBD. The Ipswich Motorway is accessible via Richlands Road, giving strong road connectivity for those who drive. Buyers who are comparing Inala to Forest Lake or Darra will often find that Inala's bus frequency and its proximity to Darra Station makes the suburb more practical for car-free living than its price might suggest. Rental demand here is consistently strong: the suburb's affordability, diversity and transport links draw a reliable tenant pool, and vacancy rates reflect that. Investors comparing yields to inner-ring suburbs will find Inala holds up well. What buyers are typically searching for in Inala are post-war brick homes on full-sized blocks, ideally in the quieter residential streets away from the main arterials, with enough room to improve or add a second dwelling over time.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The competitive set for Inala buyers is typically Darra, Richlands and Oxley, and sometimes Forest Lake for those with a slightly larger budget. Each of those suburbs has something slightly different to offer, but Inala holds its own on block size and land value relative to purchase price. Sellers in Inala benefit from the breadth of that buyer pool: a well-presented home at the right price attracts genuine competition from multiple buyer types, not just one segment. Understanding which buyers to target, and how to position a property for maximum reach, is where local knowledge makes a real difference to the outcome.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
